subtitle: Hello, I'm Jeffrey Mishlove. You know,
today is Monday, the 2nd of July. I am now
preparing a monologue that will be
released early in the morning tomorrow.
I realize one of the advantages of
not having a backlog is that it gives me
an opportunity to respond immediately
when viewers post comments to previous
videos and an immediate response
is sometimes called for. Now, one of the
viewers, I think John Paul is his name,
said I haven't been talking about the
divine feminine. He said, "I want you
to do it as soon as possible." The divine
feminine. Actually, I can tell you
this, there is an interview with James P.
Driscoll on the godhead archetype.
He's very explicit that in Western
culture, the godhead archetype as
analyzed by Carl Jung, the great Swiss
depth psychologist is lacking in a
feminine principle. That's one of the
big gaps in Western culture. Now, Jung
suggests it could be maybe the Virgin
Mary is the closest really that we get
to the idea of the
divine feminine in Western culture.
Well, there's a relationship between
feminism and the divine feminine. I
know a number of viewers get upset when
I say I'm a feminist, but one of the
reasons I am a feminist is in
relationship to the divine feminine.
Because, as a parapsychologist, probably
the most marginalized of all legitimate
sciences, I'm aware of a certain affinity
that I have for other marginalized
groups. Well, what are the other
marginalized groups? Women, people of
color, indigenous people around the
world, people from the Southern
hemisphere as opposed to the Northern
hemisphere, people who practice
alternative religions such as witchcraft,
shamanism, Gnosticism. Well, all of
these people haveâ€¦ all of these groups of
people have a greater affinity for what
you could call the intuitive factor.
According to Jung, consciousness itself,
human consciousness has four primary
factors: thinking, feeling, sensing and
intuiting. Of these our culture seems
to provide the least support for the
intuitive function. Thinkers do well, and
I fortunately was always rewarded as a
child in school because I could think
and I did well on my tests, which is both
an advantage and a disadvantage. Because
when you do well on taking tests then
what you want to do is live a life where
you can take lots of tests. Of
course, life is a lot more than taking
tests. In my lifetime I realize that I have
taken a lot of tests. I've passed various
licenses as a psychologist, as a real
estate professional, as a commodity
training advisor. Well, when you pursue a
career in parapsychology, it's a good
idea to have some back ups. Because
although I've been a parapsychologist
my whole adult life it has not been my
major source of income. Well, you know
that wasn't exactly a tangent, that was
relevant because we're talking about the
divine feminine and how, as I've pointed
out, the divine feminine gets suppressed
in Western culture. When you talk to most
people about God
they use the masculine pronoun, God = he.
That's the Judaeo-Christian tradition, God
is a he. Now, as a student of Kabbalah I
can tell you that in Jewish culture
there is a female component of the
divine. It's called the Shekhinah. The
Shekhinah is sometimes thought of as the
presence of God, sometimes thought of as
the Sabbath Queen. There's a song that
we used to sing on Friday the night
services: Come on Sabbath Day, And bring
peace and healing on thy wing.
And to every troubled breast, Sing of thy
divine behest. Thou shalt rest,
Thou shalt rest. That song is, to my
way of thinking, considered sort of an
expression of the divine feminine. It's
welcome, as the Jewish people would say,
the Sabbath Queen. Well,
the Sabbath Queen is another way of
referring to the feminine presence of
God. In the Jewish tradition, the
welcoming of the Sabbath, all of the
rituals that take place, not in the
synagogue but in the house, are often the
domain of the female head of the house.
The blessings on the candles for the Sabbath,
for example. Now, of course, I'm not an
Orthodox Jew. There may be Orthodox Jews
who take issue with this and I know they
have very sexist attitudes, I'm sorry to
say, but it's true.
There's a story in my family, for example,
and I think maybe it expresses the
ambivalence that
comes out of Judaism with regard to the
feminine. My grandmother Anna Mishlove
died when I was five years old. I never
knew her well. But my Aunt Janette, her
daughter - may she rest in peace, may they
both rest in peace - tells a story about
in the [early] 1940's my dad,
Janette's younger brother, was off in
the military. Janette was living
with my grandmother at the time before
she got married. She learned that the
Lubavitcher Rebbe, actually from Lebovitch
in Russia, was speaking at a conference
of rabbis in Chicago. Now, my family lived
in Berlin, Wisconsin, a tiny little town.
My grandmother was so eager to see
this rabbi that she and my aunt travelled
by train from Fond Du Lac 120 miles to
Chicago. They went to the restaurant,
the Jewish Deli I guess where the
conference was going on in the back
room. Now,
I should say this. My grandmother was an
orphan, her parents had died. She was
raised in a very religious family and
she was born in Russia. She came from a
part of... well, it was then Russia, it would
be Belorussia today, I think, what's
known as the Russian Pale, areas where
Jews were allowed to live near the
town of Lebovitch. Now, my grandmother
was very devout. She used to try and
study with the boys when the rabbi would
come for religious instructions. But
these were forbidden to girls. But the
rabbi would allow her to sit just
outside the room, on the other side of
the door with the door partially open so
she could hear and participate
in the instructions that were being given.
Now, many, many years later my
grandmother is an American citizen,
she has grown children, and is coming to
Chicago and the rabbi, of course, an
orthodox Lubavitcher Rebbe is never
supposed to even touch a woman. My
aunt and grandmother are sitting in the
restaurant. They want to talk to the
rabbi who is in the private meeting room.
They pass a note to him saying, "Anna
Schwam," that was her maiden name, "is
here to see you."
Eventually the rabbi came out and my
aunt was so impressed.
She said, "That rabbi, that man that is
never supposed to touch women, gave my
mother, your grandmother, a huge hug.
Unheard of." But it was because they had a
close connection. It was because, I think,
that rabbi, a Lebovitcher Hasidic rabbi,
understood something about the divine
feminine. [He] understood that yes, of course
there are many rules about keeping men
and women separate, not only in the
Jewish religion but in other religions
as well. But that separation ought not to
mean exclusive dominance by men. Because
as men begin to dominate women what
happens is the psychological functions
associated primarily with masculinity,
thinking and sensing, are accentuated. And
the psychological functions that are
mostly associated with the feminine side,
feeling and intuition, get diminished.
As intuition gets diminished, so does
psychic functioning. It's not
acknowledged in our culture. So, we live
in a very off balanced culture because
of that, because we don't acknowledge the
divine feminine. As such we don't
acknowledge
the power of women in our own culture.
For example, people say why am I a
feminist? They say, "Look at how powerful
women are. They are ruining men's lives
everywhere. They control all the money."
People have gone on and on
about why they are not feminists. But, why
I am a feminist is sort of like this:
women are making great progress now
moving into the world of business, not
being relegated to just being at home.
If women keep making this kind of
progress in business, why in just another
1,500 years we'll have full equality.
Well, why not today?
Why is it that the average woman earns
70 cents on the dollar compared to men
doing the exact same job? To me it's
a question of simple justice. Not only
simple justice but a question of... I'm a
feminist not so much for women but for
myself because I think that the
imbalance that we have in our culture
hurts men as well. Like little boys who
are taught at around the age of 7
or 8 to be a man and stop crying. And
so, little boys learn how to suppress
their feelings. Men with suppressed
feelings,
well, they create all kinds of problems
in our culture. Perhaps there are
problems for women as well who don't
get the respect that they ought to get
when they do have masculine qualities
like a fine mathematical mind. I would
like to see balance restored to our
culture And that balance goes all the
way up to our understanding of the
nature of the divine as we conceive
of it and all the way down to simple
issues of
who's going to do the dishes, how is the
housework going to be divided,
how are relationships going to be
managed? Should one sex be dominated?
Should there be laws regarding what
women can do with their bodies, but men
are not required to have similar
restrictions placed on them, for example?
All of this, I think, is about how we
ultimately treat ourselves, how we treat
our psyche. There's a sense in Jungian
psychology that the psyche is sort of
the opposite of the ego. If you have a
masculine ego then your subconscious
is your anima, its effeminate. But if we
are in a culture in which this female or
feminine is oppressed, then men aren't
as able to get in touch with their own
subconscious. So, this imbalance affects
all of us, I think, very deeply. Those are
my thoughts. I'm happy to read whatever
comments you would like to post about
this. But, let me ask you this question:
Where do you stand in relationship to
the divine feminine? Do you allow the
Shekhinah, the feminine presence of God
into your life? Well, maybe you don't
allow any presence of God into your life
because you think its a stupid concept
or something. I don't know. But give it
some thought. Give it some thought.
How do you react to the imbalances in
our culture with regard to male and
female? I'll leave you with that question.
Thank you for being with me.
